@muhdiversity7409 Yes. Yes, she did. There will be plenty of people who say we are projecting by making such a claim, but especially those who have worked in the corporate world have seen this time and time again.  Every so often, there's a scheming, bitter soul - usually female, but not always - that has tagged along with a successful group, dined in their success, but told themselves that they people who carried them along for years had in fact, "denied them." And now it's "time for revenge." In every case I've seen, not once has the spiteful brat once unleashed demonstrate even half the creativity and leadership of the "weakest" of the crew that had carried them along. It's always spite. It's always jealousy that lied to itself because these people could never accept that they were never truly as good as their companions. 

What's sad is if they had understood their role, they could have realized they _did_ actually have skills of their own. They _did_ contribute to the success of their friends, even if it was just a small part. Isn't that true with any recipe? Sometimes just that small added ingredient elevates it from "good" to "great." 

Here's to Kathleen Kennedy -- a prime example of someone who was about to be a revered chapter in history, but due to jealousy and bitterness, has become a cautionary footnote.  What more needs to be said.

